# Fleet Map — Google Maps loader contract

`src/features/fleet-map/components/MapView.tsx` wraps the map in
`<APIProvider>` from `@vis.gl/react-google-maps` (libraries=`['places', 'marker']`).
`<APIProvider>` is the **sole authorized loader** of the Google Maps JS API
for the Fleet Map. Do **not** also call `useGoogleMapsLoader()` from within
the FleetMap component tree.

## Why

`useGoogleMapsLoader` (in `src/hooks/useGoogleMapsLoader.ts`) is a legacy
helper that manually injects `<script src="https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?key=...&libraries=places&loading=async">`
into the DOM. If both loaders are active, the parent component's hook fires
first (so the legacy script tag wins), and by the time `<APIProvider>` mounts
and calls `js-api-loader.importLibrary('maps')`, `window.google.maps` already
exists. `js-api-loader` then emits the documented warning:

> `[@googlemaps/js-api-loader] No options were set before calling importLibrary. Make sure to configure the loader using setOptions().`

The Maps API is bootstrapped without the `'marker'` library and without the
proper async-loader handshake required by the **WebGL vector tile renderer**.
DOM-overlay markers still render (they project lat/lng to screen coords
without needing tiles), but the basemap silently never fetches a single tile.
Symptoms: map area is rendered, markers and the legend appear, but the
basemap stays blank. This is exactly what regressed FleetMap on
`preview.equipqr.app` (issue #617).

## The rule

In `src/features/fleet-map/pages/FleetMap.tsx` and any other component that
mounts `<MapView>`:

- **DO:** `import { useGoogleMapsKey } from '@/hooks/useGoogleMapsKey'` and
  pass the returned `googleMapsKey` + `mapId` down to `<MapView>`.
- **DO NOT:** import `useGoogleMapsLoader` from `@/hooks/useGoogleMapsLoader`.

`useGoogleMapsKey` only fetches the API key + Map ID from the
`public-google-maps-key` Edge Function; it does not inject any `<script>` tag.

## When `useGoogleMapsLoader` IS appropriate

Other surfaces that need the Maps JS API but do **not** wrap content in
`<APIProvider>` (e.g. `TeamLocationCard`, `EquipmentDetailsTab`,
`GooglePlacesAutocomplete`, equipment form location pickers) should keep
using `useGoogleMapsLoader` because they need the legacy script injection.

If you migrate any of those surfaces to `<APIProvider>` in the future, switch
their loader to `useGoogleMapsKey` at the same time to avoid reintroducing
the dual-loader race.

## Reference

- Original incident: [#617](https://github.com/Columbia-Cloudworks-LLC/EquipQR/issues/617)
- Fix commit: `27d81255` — `fix(fleet-map): drop legacy script-loader to let APIProvider own Maps init`
- Migration that introduced the dual-loader hazard: PR #616 (`@react-google-maps/api` → `@vis.gl/react-google-maps`)
- Operator runbook for the upstream Google Cloud API key's HTTP-referrer allowlist (separate from the Supabase secret value): [docs/ops/supabase-branch-secrets.md → Google Maps API key — HTTP referrer allowlist](../../docs/ops/supabase-branch-secrets.md#google-maps-api-key--http-referrer-allowlist). The Fleet Map's `MapsAuthFailureCard` (in `src/features/fleet-map/components/MapView.tsx`) renders an in-app diagnostic when Google fires `gm_authFailure` — the page URL it shows is the exact entry the operator must add to the API key's allowlist.
